    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = Cristina Bishop\n|children      = 3\n|education     = [[University of Michigan|University of Michigan, Ann Arbor]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Michigan State University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website        = {{url|mikebishop.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Michael Dean Bishop''' (born March 18, 1967) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MI|8}} since 2015. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He previously served in the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] from 1999 to 2003, and the [[Michigan State Senate]] from 2002-10 where he served as [[majority leader]].<ref>[http://legislature.mi.gov/(S(xkgik3j0k3pt4255nehxgjiy))/documents/2009-2010/michiganmanual/2009-MM-p0145-p0145.pdf 2009\u20132010 Michigan Manual: State Senator Michael D. Bishop profile], legislature.mi.gov; accessed January 16, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2018}}\nBishop graduated from [[Rochester Adams High School]], and graduated from [[University of Michigan]] in 1989. He received a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Michigan State University College of Law]]. Bishop is also a licensed [[real estate broker]] and has owned two local real estate businesses, Freedom Realty, Inc. and Pro Management, Inc. Bishop is a member of the [[American Bar Association]], [[State Bar of Michigan]], [[District of Columbia Bar]], Bar of the Supreme Court of the United States, Oakland County Bar Association, Michigan Association of Realtors, and [[National Association of Realtors]].\n\nHe served on the Municipal Law and Business Law committees of the Oakland County Bar Association and is a member of the National Association of Sportsmen Legislators. Following his time in the Michigan Legislature, Bishop worked as Chief Legal Officer for International Bancard Corporation and taught at [[Thomas M. Cooley Law School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mikebishop.house.gov/about|title=About|work=Congressman Mike Bishop|accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref> Prior to his election in the 45th District ,Bishop unsuccessfully campaigned for a [[University of Michigan Board of Regents]] position in 1996.<ref>Demas, S. [http://domemagazine.com/blogs/bishop Bishop was Born to Run]; domemagazine.com, March 16, 2009; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref> \n\n==Michigan legislature==\n\n=== Michigan House of Representatives ===\nBishop served in the Michigan State House from 1999 to 2002 representing the 45th District, which covered much of the same territory where his father, Donald Bishop, had served.<ref>Demas, S. [http://domemagazine.com/blogs/bishop Bishop was Born to Run]; domemagazine.com, March 16, 2009; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref> During his four-year tenure in the Michigan House, he served as vice chairman of the Commerce Committee.<ref>[http://www.lwvoa.org/files/Voter2008_01.pdf Oakland Voter]; League of Women Voters Oakland Area, January 2008; retrieved March 24, 2017.</ref>\n\n=== Michigan Senate ===\nBishop was  elected to the State Senate in 2002 represented the 12th District, a seat which had previously been held by his father. He served until [[term limits]] prevented him from re-election in 2010.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/152471/mike-bishop Mike Bishop's Biography on Votesmart]; votesmart.com; retrieved March 25, 2017.</ref> Before his time as majority leader, Bishop was chosen to be chairman of the Banking and Financial Institutions Committee<ref>Lane, A.[http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20060925/SUB/60922004 40 Under 40]; Crain\u2019s Detroit Business, September 25, 2006; retrieved March 24, 2017</ref> and vice chairman of both the Gaming and Casino Oversight Committee and Judiciary Committee.{{Uncited|date=September 2018}}\n\n==== Majority Leader ====\nBishop was the Senate Majority Leader from 2007-2010. During this time, a bill to create the [[Gordie Howe International Bridge]] as a companion to the [[Ambassador Bridge]] came to him for determination to put it to the Senate floor for a vote. Corporate and business interests were strongly in favor of the bill which would partner with Canada to pay for the bridge. Despite promising to put the bill on the floor for a vote Bishop reneged, according to former Michigan Governor and ambassador to Canada Jim Blanchard. Governor Snyder found another way to make the deal however and the project continued without Bishop's support.<ref>Lessenbury, J. [http://michiganradio.org/post/mike-bishop-about-become-matty-morouns-man-congress#stream/0 Mike Bishop about to become Matty Moroun's man in Congress], October 22, 2014; retrieved August 31, 2016.</ref><ref>Lessenberry, J. [http://www.metrotimes.com/detroit/politics-and-prejudices-matty-morouns-very-own-congressman/Content?oid=2263345 Politics and Prejudices: Matty Moroun's very own congressman]; metrotimes.com, October 29, 2014; retrieved August 31, 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.metrotimes.com/detroit/bridge-brigade/Content?oid=2150514 Bridge brigade DRIC supporters pressure Bishop for the vote he promised], metrotimes.com, November 24, 2010; retrieved August 31, 2016.</ref>\n\nAt the State Republican Party Convention in 2010, Bishop unsuccessfully bid for the Republican nomination for state attorney general.<ref>Wieder, B [http://time.com/3759288/manoj-bhargava-campaign-finance/?iid=sr-link3 The Political Kingmaker Nobody Knows]; time.com, March 26, 2015; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref> He ran for Oakland County prosecutor in 2012, but lost to Democratic incumbent Jessica R. Cooper.<ref>[http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/MI/Oakland/43747/114561/en/summary.html Oakland County Clerk/Register of Deeds] November 6, 2012; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref><ref>Gonzales, N. [http://www.rollcall.com/news/home/freshman-class-filled-with-losers Freshman Class Filled with Losers]; rollcall.com, November 24, 2014; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nBefore being elected to the US House of Representatives he vowed to vote to block the Gordie Howe International bridge. The ''Livingston Daily'' reported \"A proposal for the federal government to fund a U.S. customs center has stalled. If elected, Bishop said he wouldn't support federal funding of the customs center.\"<ref>Behnan, C. [http://www.livingstondaily.com/story/news/politics/elections/michigan/2014/10/19/bridge-funding-obamacare-separate-schertzing-bishop-th-congressional-race/17592777 \"Bridge funding, Obamacare separate Schertzing, Bishop in 8th Congressional race], livingstondaily.com, October 19, 2014; retrieved August 31, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Elections===\n;2014\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2014#District 8}}\nOn November 4, 2014, Bishop defeated Democratic challenger Eric Schertzing for Michigan's 8th congressional district.<ref>[http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/elections/2014/11/04/michigan-congress-eighth-district-election-results/18491127 Bishop defeats Schertzing for 8th District congressional race], detroitnews.com; accessed November 30, 2014.</ref>\n\nBishop was sworn in on January 6, 2015. Shortly after being sworn in, he voted for [[John Boehner]] as Speaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/saginaw/index.ssf/2015/01/speaker_john_boehner_is_reelec.html|title=Speaker John Boehner is reelected: How Michigan's delegation voted|work=[[MLive.com]]|accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n;2016\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2016#District 8}}\nBishop successfully ran for re-election in 2016. He ran unopposed in the Republican primary. Two Democrats, actress [[Melissa Gilbert]] and Linda Keefe, filed to run in the Democratic primary election. Gilbert later withdrew.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peal|first1=Wayne|title=Gilbert, Bishop spar over finances|url=http://www.livingstondaily.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/04/16/melissa-gilbert-congress-contributions/83124910|accessdate=April 29, 2016|publisher=Livingston Daily|date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Gilbert was replaced with Democratic challenger Suzanna Shkreli late in the race in July, 2016.<ref>Ooosting, J. and Laing, K. [http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/11/08/michigan-congress-district-shkreli-bishop-results/93498344/ District 8: Rep. Bishop wins re-election over Shkreli], detroitnews.com, November 8, 2016; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, Homeland Security and Investigations|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, Homeland Security and Investigations]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law|Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n**[[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Oversight|Subcommittee on Oversight]]\n**[[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Human Resources|Subcommittee on Human Resources]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n* [[House Baltic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Positions ==\n\n=== Abortion ===\nBishop is pro-life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liveaction.org/news/along-with-trump-win-americans-elect-prolife-house-senate/|title=Along with Trump win, Americans elect a pro-life House and Senate|website=www.liveaction.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> He has voted to ban abortions after 20 weeks and has co-sponsored legislation which states that life starts at conception.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/mike-bishop/|title=Tracking Congress In The Age Of Trump|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron|date=2017-01-30|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/05/24/abortion-rights-group-launches-5-million-campaign-to-flip-the-house/|title=Abortion rights group launches $5 million campaign to flip the House|last=https://www.facebook.com/daveweigel?fref=ts|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Affordable Care Act ===\nBishop disapproves of the ACA and voted to repeal the Affordable Care Act in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mikebishop.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=90|title=Bishop Fights for Families Hurt by Obamacare|date=2016-01-06|website=U.S. Congressman Mike Bishop|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2016/10/21/bishop-shkreli-congress/92501102/|title=Bishop in a heated race to stay in Congress|work=Detroit News|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Animal testing ===\nBishop has called on the [[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]] to stop the killing of kittens after being tested on for research.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2018/05/08/bishop-kittens-usda-experiments/34686859/|title=Bishop presses USDA on kittens killed after research|work=Detroit News|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/news/437856-us-lab-kitten-experiment/|title=US govt blocks info release on thousands of kittens experimented & killed at Maryland lab \u2013 lawsuit|work=RT International|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/08/politics/usda-maryland-kitten-research/index.html|title=Congressman wants answers from USDA on cats allegedly killed during government research|last=CNN|first=Juana Summers,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Guns ===\nBishop supports gun rights and the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]], receiving a A/A+ rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theoaklandpress.com/news/dataworks/gun-rights-vs-gun-control-will-mass-killings-elevate-the/article_5bcaa22d-7208-5b67-bbaf-c5a5f0fc556a.html|title=Gun Rights vs Gun Control: Will mass killings elevate the debate during this year\u2019s congressional elections?|last=Crumm|first=Charles|work=TheOaklandPress.com|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nFollowing Bishop\u2019s actions in the Michigan Senate concerning the Detroit-Windsor bridge vote, critics pointed to donations Bishop received from [[Manuel Moroun]], owner of the CenTra, Inc., which controls the [[Ambassador Bridge]], as a corrupting factor.<ref>Oosting, J. [http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2010/11/dric_watch_critics_accuse_mike.html DRIC watch: Critics accuse Mike Bishop of stalling Michigan Senate vote on Detroit-Windsor bridge after receiving donations from Manuel Moroun], mlive.com, November 10, 2010, retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref><ref>Wattrick, J. [http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2012/01/oaklands_choice_the_depressing.html Oakland's Choice: The depressing prospect of a Jessica Cooper-Mike Bishop matchup in County Prosecutor's race], mlive.com, January 5, 2012; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref> During his campaign for the U.S. Congress in 2014, similar criticism about Bishop\u2019s connections to Moroun emerged.<ref>Lessenberry, J. [http://michiganradio.org/post/mike-bishop-about-become-matty-morouns-man-congress Mike Bishop about to Become Matty Moroun's Man in Congress], michiganradio.org, October 22, 2014; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref>  Following his election to congress, Bishop continued to be seen as an ally of the Moroun family going back to his days in the state House.<ref>Spangler, T. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/09/13/boehner-fundraiser-moroun-ambassador-bridge-detroit-michigan-canada/72209604/ Wealthy Detroit bridge-owning family throws $25,000-plate dinner for Boehner], usatoday.com, September 13, 2015; retrieved March 21, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBishop, a resident of [[Rochester, Michigan]], is married and has three children.<ref>{{cite news|author=Fritz Klug|title=Mike Bishop ready to take Michigan legislative experience to Washington DC |newspaper=Mlive.com|date=January 2, 2015|url=http://www.mlive.com/lansing-news/index.ssf/2015/01/mike_bishop_ready_to_take_mich.html|accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref> He is a [[Congregational church|Congregationalist]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Members of Congress: Religious Affiliations|url=http://www.pewforum.org/2015/01/05/members-of-congress-religious-affiliations |accessdate=April 29, 2016|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://mikebishop.house.gov/ Congressman Mike Bishop] official U.S. House website\n* [http://www.electmikebishop.com/ Campaign website]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Michigan/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Mike_Bishop_%5BR-8%5D|Mike Bishop}}\n*{{ CongLinks | congbio = B001293 | fec = H4MI08135 | votesmart = 152471 | congress = mike-bishop/B001293}}\n* {{C-SPAN|mikebishop}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Michigan\n| district=8\n| before=[[Mike Rogers (Michigan politician)|Mike Rogers]]\n| start=January 3, 2015\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Don Beyer]]<br>D-[[Virginia]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=317th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rod Blum]]<br>R-[[Iowa]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 114th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Michigan]]}}\n{{USCongRep/MI/114}}\n{{USCongRep/MI/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{MI-FedRep}}\n{{U.S. Michigan Representatives}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bishop, Mike}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Michigan State University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Michigan state senators]]\n[[Category:Michigan Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Almont, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Rochester, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Detroit College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]"}]}}}}